  "text": "The top row identifies a measured or computed ERG parameter. a max is the saturating amplitude of the a-wave component of the ERG (Fig. 6) , and b max the saturating amplitudes of the gaussian-filtered b-wave, obtained under cone-isolation conditions (Fig. 4A) . S M and S UV are the relative sensitivities of the cone-driven b-wave in the midwave and UV spectral regions, derived as follows. The peak amplitudes of gaussian-filtered cone b-wave responses were obtained in the linear region of the amplitude versus intensity function and were normalized by the amplitude of the saturating response (Fig. 4B) ; S M was calculated as the average of all data obtained with 492, 501, and 513 nm flashes, and S UV is the mean of all data obtained with 346, 356, and 361 nm flashes. S UV /S M is the ratio, determined separately for each animal. The errors given are SDs. *The observations in parentheses are taken from [CITATION_1] and were obtained in the presence of a steady background estimated to produce 6000 photoisomerizations rod Ϫ1 sec Ϫ1 and shown to suppress at least 95% of the rod circulating current. To obviate a possible residual contribution from the rod a-wave that may have contaminated this previous estimate of the cone a max in some mice, the measurements of the cone a-waves of WT mice reported in this table (n ϭ 4) were all obtained in a double-flash paradigm, which measures the cone response a few seconds after the rod a-wave is suppressed with a very intense flash [CITATION_2] and which takes advantage of the very rapid recovery of the cone a-wave (Figs. 6, 7) . , suppressing rod signals [CITATION_3] ; for all other recordings, rod activity was suppressed with the conditioning flash. Each trace is the average of 10 records. B, Recovery in GRK1 Ϫ/Ϫ mouse; each trace is the average of five measurements. C, Recovery in Arrestin Ϫ/Ϫ mouse; each trace is the average of 15 records.",
